fields:
water molecules are liquid at room temperature with a high surface tension and boiling point because.
  • {{c1:: The hydrogen bonds between oxygen and hydrogen of different molecules are constantly forming and breaking due to heat. In this sense, water is essentially a network. }}
The four main small organic molecules are {{c1::fatty acids}}, {{c2::nucleotides}}, {{c3::amino acids}}, and {{c4::sugars}}
A {{c1::condensation}} reaction is when {{c2::two monomers join, one has a —H and the other a —OH. The two monomers join and emit a H2O}}. This reaction is energetically {{c3::unfavorable}}.
A {{c1::hydrolysis}} reaction is when {{c2::a polymer is split, one of the monomer terminals takes an H and the other takes an OH}}. This reaction is energetically {{c3::favorable}}.
The inverse of a {{c1::hydrolysis}} reaction is a {{c2::condensation}} reaction.
The two types of metabolic pathways are {{c1::catabolic (emits energy by breaking down molecules)}} and {{c2::anabolic (consumes energy to synthesize molecules)}}.
In a carbon atom, a(n) {{c1::reduction}} reaction occurs when the number of {{c2::C—H}} bonds increase.
In a carbon atom, a(n) {{c1::oxidation}} reaction occurs when the number of {{c2::C—H}} bonds decrease.
{{c1::Hydrogenation}} is when an atom picks up a {{c2::electron}} and a {{c2::proton}} at the same time.
[T/F]: Enzymes can change the direction of a reaction. {{c1::false}}.
Enzymes lower the energy required to reverse a reaction by the same magnitude that the lower the energy required for the normal reaction.
The electron carrier {{c1::NADH}} is an intermediary protein involved in the generation of {{c2::ATP}} in {{c2::catabolic}} reactions.
{{c1::NADPH}} interacts with enzymes involved in {{c2::anabolic reactions}}, serving the purpose of {{c2::supplying the electron needed for expensive anabolic reactions}}.
{{c1::Glycogen}} is used for short-term storage of energy, taking the form of a {{c2::large polysaccharide polymer}} composed of {{c3::glucose}} subunits.
The biggest stores of {{c1::Glycogen}} are in the liver and muscle. The liver breaks down and releases its {{c2::polysaccharides}} when {{c3::sugar}} is scarce, where muscles hoard their own.
Glycogen is stored in {{c1::the cytoplasm of cells}}.
{{c1::Triglycerides}} take the form of {{c2::lipids}}, with one {{c3::glycerol}} molecule bound to three {{c3::fatty acid chains}}.
{{c1::Triglycerides}} are used for long-term energy storage and {{c1::Glycogen}} are used for short-term energy storage.
Two common types of structures found in proteins: {{c1::alpha helices}} and {{c1::beta sheets}}
Is the 3D structure or the amino acid sequence more conserved in proteins? {{c1::structure}}
Some {{c1::macromolecular complexes}} require enzymes that {{c1::assist with building the complex}}, called {{c2::assembly factors}}
Some {{c1::macromolecular complexes}} form spontaneously when {{c2::their subunits are dissociated and mixed together}}, like the tobacco mosaic virus and ribosomes.

{{c1::feedback}} or {{c1::negative inhibition}} is when a {{c2::product from a reaction late in a pathway inhibits an enzyme upstream of the pathway to slow the catalysis as the end product accumulates}}.
The term for when {{c1::a molecule binds to a protein and changes its function by causing a change in its conformation}} is called {{c2::allostery}}.
{{c1::phosphorylation}} refers to the process of {{c2::adding a phosphate group to a protein through a covalent bond}}

Three common ways in which phosphate groups affect protein function
  • {{c1:: phosphates have two negative charges, so they affect protein conformation }}
  • {{c3:: they can inhibit active sites }}
  • {{c4:: they can form parts of structures recognized by other proteins }}
a {{c1::phosphatase}} is {{c2::an enzyme that removes a phosphate group from a protein}}.
a {{c1::protein kinase}} catalyzes a reaction in which {{c2::an ATP phosphorylates the hydroxyl group on a serine, threonine or tyrosine sidechain of a protein.}}

{{c1::multivalent macromolecules}} are scaffold macromolecules that {{c2::have binding sites for itself and numerous other proteins or RNA molecules, and the binding sites are weak allowing frequent binding and dissociation}}

{{c1::biomolecular condensates}} are weaker, less structured aggregates of {{c2::RNA molecules and proteins}} that are {{c2::less rigid and specific in their conformation than common macromolecular complexes such as ribosomes}}. They speed up reactions by {{c2::helping to keep certain proteins localized to certain regions of a cell to increase their local concentration}}.
A {{c1::tRNA (transfer RNA)}} is a molecule that {{c2::matches codons with an anticodon and attaches amino acids to the growing polypeptide chain.}}
{{c1::plants}} fix {{c2::carbon}}, and {{c1::bacteria in the ground}} fix {{c2::nitrogen}}

Four common sources of gene changes
  • {{c1:: gene duplication }}
  • {{c3:: intragenic mutation }}
  • {{c4:: dna segment shuffling }}
  • {{c5:: horizontal dna transfer }}
{{c1::othologs}}: {{c2::genes that differ due to a speciation event}}
{{c1::paralogs}}: {{c2::genes that differ due to gene duplication and divergence in the same species}}
{{c1::homologs}}: {{c2::the word for a relationship between genes that are either orthologs or paralogs.}}
{{c1::endocytosis}}: {{c2::the process by which a cell pulls in a molecule or organelle into its cytosome, encapsulating it in a vesicle.}}
{{c1::phagocytosis}}: {{c2::the process in which a cell envelops and "eats" other cells or particles}}
{{c1::vesicles}}: {{c2::tiny lipid membranes that contain fluid and molecules}}

The organelles enclosed in double membranes are
  • {{c1:: nucleus }}
  • {{c3:: mitochondria }}
  • {{c4:: chloroplasts }}
The two most well-studied viruses that infect {{c1::e-coli}} are {{c2::lambda}} and {{c2::T4}}
{{c1::exocytosis}}: when a {{c2::vesicle}} or a {{c2::vacuole}} merges with the cell membrane and releases its contents into the extracellular fluid.
nucleotides are made up of a {{c1::sugar backbone}}, a {{c2::phosphate group}}, and a {{c3::base or nucleobase}}.
The origins of eukaryotes are when {{c1::an archaeon absorbed a bacterium}}.
The base pairs of DNA are held together by {{c1::hydrogen}} bonds
The two terminals of eukaryotic mRNA are referred to as the {{c1::3' cap}} and the {{c2::5' cap}}

m7G, which is found on the {{c1::5' cap}} of eukaryotic mRNA, stands for {{c2::7-methylguanosine}}, whose purpose is, among many things, to {{c3::protect the mRNA from degradation}}, {{c4::assist in ribosome binding for transcription}}, and {{c5::aid in nuclear export}}.
in eukaryotic cells, mRNA translation starts from the {{c1::5'}} and end of the mRNA and scans towards the {{c2::3'}} end of the mRNA.
In a strand of DNA or RNA, the end with the {{c1::phosphate}} is the {{c2::5'}} terminal and the end with the {{c1::sugar}} is the {{c2::3'}} terminal.
subsequent sugars in a DNA strand are held together by a {{c1::phosphodiester}} bond.
The DNA double helix does a complete turn every {{c1::10.4}} base pairs.
The {{c1::endoplasmic reticulum}} is a complex of intracellular folded membranes that extends from the {{c2::nucleus}} into the {{c3::cytoplasm}}
Each human cell (except for gametes and other special cases) contains {{c1::46}} chromosomes, or {{c1::23}} pairs.
Of the 23 pairs of chromosomes in normal cells, {{c1::22}} are homologs and {{c1::1}} is/are heterologs.
Which varies more from species to species? Gene count or non-coding DNA count? :-> {{c1::non-coding DNA count}}
[T/F]: How the genome is divided into chromosomes varies significantly, even in neighboring species. :-> {{c1::True}}
